18:29.776 --> 18:32.178
♪ Kongy fongy hongi bongi ♪

18:32.212 --> 18:33.479
♪ Icky wicky oh yeah ♪

18:33.514 --> 18:34.615
♪ Hongi bongi ♪

18:34.648 --> 18:35.682
♪ Hongi bongi ♪

18:35.716 --> 18:36.917
♪ Hongi bongi ♪

18:36.950 --> 18:38.418
♪ Hongi bongi... ♪

18:38.451 --> 18:40.521
Stop, stop, stop!

18:41.555 --> 18:43.524
You’re embarrassing me.

18:48.929 --> 18:50.897
Now, sit down and listen.

18:53.499 --> 18:54.535
Ahem.

18:56.537 --> 18:59.305
Once upon a time...

18:59.339 --> 19:01.775
...there was a beautiful
island in the South Pacific

19:01.808 --> 19:04.210
called Tamiki.
And the Tamiki‐ites‐‐

19:04.244 --> 19:05.879
Okay, uh, Balki,
Balki here’s a thought.

19:05.912 --> 19:08.549
Uh, why‐why don’t you,
uh, s‐sign the papers first

19:08.582 --> 19:12.352
and then do story time while
they’re making out our checks?

19:12.385 --> 19:14.187
Cousin, cousin, I’m trying
to get this story

19:14.220 --> 19:15.522
off the ground, okay?

19:15.556 --> 19:17.591
Just, just...

19:17.624 --> 19:19.793
The Tamiki‐ites were very happy.

19:19.826 --> 19:22.596
And then one day they sold
part of their island

19:22.629 --> 19:23.930
to a big corporation.

19:23.964 --> 19:26.399
Uh, the big corporation
wanted to use that land

19:26.432 --> 19:28.969
to store things.

19:29.002 --> 19:31.404
What kind of things
did they want to store?

19:31.437 --> 19:33.940
Well, we’re not talking
about things

19:33.974 --> 19:35.676
that you would store
in your garage

19:35.709 --> 19:38.211
like, uh, Christmas decorations

19:38.244 --> 19:40.781
and old National Geographic’s

19:40.814 --> 19:43.349
and the occasional Pez dispenser

19:43.383 --> 19:45.385
where the candy comes out
of the fish head.

19:46.987 --> 19:50.691
No. They wanted to store
some other kind of things.

19:50.724 --> 19:53.694
So...after a while

19:53.727 --> 19:55.829
the palm trees started to die

19:55.862 --> 19:59.733
and the water
started to smell bad

19:59.766 --> 20:02.569
and the Tamiki‐ites
started to get sick.

20:02.603 --> 20:04.571
And pretty soon
they had to move away

20:04.605 --> 20:06.006
from their beautiful island home

20:06.039 --> 20:08.709
because it wasn’t
beautiful anymore.

20:08.742 --> 20:10.644
What the big corporation
was storing there

20:10.677 --> 20:13.714
was toxic waste.

20:13.747 --> 20:15.015
And do you know
what is the name

20:15.048 --> 20:17.450
of the corporation
that did this to Tamiki?

20:17.483 --> 20:18.919
I’m feeling a little queasy.

20:18.952 --> 20:20.887
Do you have any saltines?

20:22.789 --> 20:24.324
The name of the corporation

20:24.357 --> 20:26.259
is Seifert Incorporated.

20:27.928 --> 20:29.730
Seifert Incorporated?

20:29.763 --> 20:31.998
Well‐well, Balki, that’s
a‐a very interesting fact

20:32.032 --> 20:34.801
but these nice people work
for Worldwide Amalgamated.

20:34.835 --> 20:36.937
So, let’s sign the papers.

20:38.539 --> 20:41.975
Worldwide Amalgamated
owns Seifert Incorporated.

20:42.008 --> 20:43.610
Babasticki!

20:47.013 --> 20:48.582
I learned this fact when I took

20:48.615 --> 20:50.584
the microfilm back
to the archives.

20:50.617 --> 20:52.686
And I would like
to take this opportunity

20:52.719 --> 20:56.389
to thank my official negotiating
adviser, Cousin Larry

20:56.422 --> 20:59.760
for suggesting that I show
the microfilm on the machine.

21:03.096 --> 21:05.632
I’m sorry, gentlemen.
We have no deal.

21:05.666 --> 21:07.568
Good day, gentlemen.

21:07.601 --> 21:09.536
Find me another island.

21:14.040 --> 21:15.976
‐No deal?
‐No deal.

21:16.009 --> 21:17.611
‐No deal?
‐No deal.

21:17.644 --> 21:20.013
But I wanted a deal.

21:20.046 --> 21:22.783
I wanted to have a deal.

21:34.928 --> 21:38.732
Come on, cousin. Come on.

21:38.765 --> 21:41.401
Just think of it...
Think of it this way.

21:41.434 --> 21:43.837
We saved the lives
of everyone on Mypos.

21:45.539 --> 21:48.374
Well, I guess
that’s a good thing.

21:50.711 --> 21:53.079
But all that money.

21:53.113 --> 21:54.948
Cousin, I know. I know.

21:54.981 --> 21:57.083
I know. Come on, come on.

21:57.117 --> 21:59.085
Ah, you’re right.

21:59.119 --> 22:00.386
[sighing]

22:00.420 --> 22:02.488
We did a good thing.

22:02.523 --> 22:03.657
Well, actually, uh

22:03.690 --> 22:06.693
you’re the one
who did the good thing.

22:06.727 --> 22:09.963
I was just trying
to do the best thing for Mypos.

22:09.996 --> 22:11.565
Well, you did.

22:12.432 --> 22:13.834
[sighing]

22:16.937 --> 22:18.471
I can understand
why they asked you

22:18.505 --> 22:21.041
to be the official negotiator.

22:21.074 --> 22:23.109
That King Ferdinand is no fool.

22:23.143 --> 22:24.811
Well, of course he’s not.

22:24.845 --> 22:26.580
Don’t be ridiculous.

22:29.149 --> 22:31.718
He just likes
to wear the outfit.

22:33.654 --> 22:35.589
